{
  "text": "Given a combinatorial line \u2113 : [CITATION_1] \u2192 [CITATION_2] n , we define its length |\u2113| to be the number of coordinates 1 \u2264 i \u2264 n for which \u2113 i (x) varies with x. For example, the line given by \u2113(x) = (3, x, 1, x, 4) has length 2. (To justify this terminology, note that |\u2113| is the Hamming distance between the two endpoints \u2113(1) and \u2113(4), or indeed between any two points of \u2113.)",
